snippet.textDisplay: The only thing I am having a tough time with is all these little comments trying their hardest to break down the positive message Dwayne, his family, and Ellen are trying to spread. I had to report some of them because it's just unnecessary. We get it, you dislike the LGBTQ+ and you're transphobic, you're the people they were talking about being unsafe. Sometimes it just makes me sad that there are still so many people that think that way and act that way online, because you never know when they would act on it in person. Stop making people feel unsafe and unwanted, even if Zaya doesn't fully transition, or if/when she does it is none of your business. Her journey no one else's. Her family is supporting her and that is the best thing she could have, so your ignorance isn't welcome. Love Dwayne, his family, and Ellen for promoting positivity and encouraging others to love their children. I always feel for all the kids that are mistreated because their parents aren't willing to really love them enough to walk with them on their journey or accept them however they are.

snippet.textDisplay: Before you get offended, think about the statement I'm going to make. Love and support are two DIFFERENT things. A parent SHOULD love their child immensely and unconditionally, however, supporting or not supporting someone's lifestyle does NOT define love. My parents do not support my choice to smoke weed but that never stopped them from loving me (completely unrelated to sexuality but I used it as a comparison). Likewise, if D. Wade decided not to support his child's transition, that wouldn't make him any less of a good parent (as long as he doesn't neglet or abuse them). I'm happy that their family is happy but people should really understand the difference between those two words.

Wade decided not to support his child's transition, that wouldn't make him any less of a good parent (as long as he doesn't neglet or abuse them). I'm happy that their family is happy but people should really understand the difference between those two words.
